Title: Improve Kirigami integration on iOS

## Problem

`kirigami_package_breeze_icons()` currently packages the Breeze icons required
by Kirigami only for Android. The macro returns immediately on every other
platform.

iOS applications cannot rely on an installed icon theme at runtime. The
required SVG files and theme index must be compiled into the application
resource system, which forces each application to duplicate Kirigami's icon
list and packaging logic.

Kirigami also has no theme definition for Qt's native iOS style, so it falls
back to the Material theme. That fallback forces light colors for most color
sets even when iOS and Qt Quick Controls are using dark appearance.

Finally, `GlobalDrawer` applies its top safe-area padding both to the complete
layout and to its top content. Its top-content column also claims all remaining
height, leaving extra space above the drawer actions.

## Proposed change

Extend `kirigami_package_breeze_icons()` with an optional `TARGET` argument and
support iOS in addition to Android.

On iOS, require a valid target, locate the installed Breeze icon theme, resolve
the requested and Kirigami-provided icons at size 22, and attach them to the
target with `qt_add_resources()` under `/icons/breeze`. Include `index.theme`
so Qt can load the embedded theme. Missing individual icons produce warnings
and do not stop configuration.

Keep the existing Android installation behavior unchanged. The `TARGET`
argument remains optional there for compatibility with existing callers.

Add an iOS theme backed by `SystemPalette` so Kirigami colors follow Qt's
native iOS palette and system appearance. Remove the duplicate top safe-area
margin and flexible-height request from `GlobalDrawer` top content. Add
regression tests that verify top padding is applied exactly once and top
content keeps its implicit height.

## Impact

iOS applications can use the same icon-name declaration as Android without
maintaining a separate list of Breeze paths or their own resource target.
Callers targeting iOS must pass the application target to the macro. Other
platforms remain no-ops, and Android packaging remains unchanged.

Kirigami components now consistently follow iOS light and dark appearance.
Drawer content retains notch protection, while actions follow top content
without the duplicated or flexible vertical gap.
